 shield, knocking me aside. Then the archers came from the woods. They were girls, about a dozen of them. The youngest was maybe ten. The oldest, about fourteen, like me. They wore silvery ski parkas and jeans, and they were all armed with bows. They advanced on the manticore with determ- ined expressions. \x{201c}The Hunters!\x{201d} Annabeth cried. Next to me, Thalia muttered, \x{201c}Oh, wonderful.\x{201d} I didn't have a chance to ask what she meant. One of the older archers stepped forward with her bow drawn. She was tall and graceful with coppery colored skin. Unlike the other girls, she had a silver circlet braided into the top of her long dark hair, so she looked like some kind of Persian princess. \x{201c}Permission to kill, my lady?\x{201d} I couldn't tell who she was talking to, because she kept her eyes on the manticore. The monster wailed. \x{201c}This is not fair! Direct interference! It is against the Ancient Laws.\x{201d} \x{201c}Not so,\x{201d} another girl said. This one was a little younger than me, maybe twelve or thir- teen. She had auburn hair gathered back in a ponytail and strange eyes, silvery yellow like the moon. Her face was so beautiful it made me catch my breath, but her expression was stern and dangerous. \x{201c}The hunting of all wild beasts is within my sphere. And you, foul creature, are a wild beast.\x{201d} She looked at the older girl with the circlet. \x{201c}Zoe, permission gran- ted.\x{201d} The manticore growled. \x{201c}If I cannot have these alive, I shall have them dead!\x{201d} He lunged at Thalia and me, knowing we were weak and dazed. \x{201c}No.'\x{201d} Annabeth yelled, and she charged at the monster. \x{201c}Get back, half-blood!\x{201d} the girl with the circlet said. \x{201c}Get out of the line of fire!\x{201d} But Annabeth leaped onto the monster's back and drove her knife into his mane. The manticore howled, turning in circles with his tail flailing as Annabeth hung on for dear life. \x{201c}Fire!\x{201d} Zoe or