ng for Annabeth?\x{201d} He had a little trouble focusing on me. Then he blushed. \x{201c}Oh, right. That too. Of course.\x{201d} \x{201c}Why?\x{201d} I asked. \x{201c}What were you thinking?\x{201d} He clopped his hooves uneasily. \x{201c}Just something the manticore said, about the Great Stir- ring. I can't help but wonder\x{2026} if all those ancient powers are waking up, maybe\x{2026} maybe not all of them are evil.\x{201d} \x{201c}You mean Pan.\x{201d} I felt kind of selfish, because I'd totally forgotten about Grover's life ambition. The nature god had gone missing two thousand years ago. He was rumored to have died, but the satyrs didn't believe that. They were determined to find him. They'd been searching in vain for cen- turies, and Grover was convinced he'd be the one to succeed. This year, with Chiron putting all the satyrs on emergency duty to find half-bloods, Grover hadn't been able to continue hissearch. It must've been driving him nuts. \x{201c}I've let the trail go cold,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}I feel restless, like I'm missing something really import- ant. He's out there somewhere. I can just feel it.\x{201d} I didn't know what to say. I wanted to encourage him, but I didn't know how. My optimism had pretty much been trampled into the snow out there in the woods, along with our cap- ture-the-flag hopes. Before I could respond, Thalia tromped up the stairs. She was officially not talking to me now, but she looked at Grover and said, \x{201c}Tell Percy to get his butt downstairs.\x{201d} \x{201c}Why?\x{201d} I asked. \x{201c}Did he say something?\x{201d} Thalia asked Grover. \x{201c}Um, he asked why.\x{201d} \x{201c}Dionysus is calling a council of cabin leaders to discuss the prophecy,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}Unfortunately, that includes Percy.\x{201d} The council was held around a Ping-Pong table in the rec room. Dionysus waved his hand and supplied snacks: Cheez Whiz, crackers, and several bottles of red wine. Then Chiron re- minded him that wine was against his restrictions and most of us were underage. Mr. D sighed. With a snap of his fingers the wine turned to Diet Coke. Nobody drank that either. Mr. D and Chiron (in wheelchair form) sat at one end of the table. Zoe and Bianca di An- gelo (who had kind of become Zoe's personal assistant) took the other end. Thalia and Grover and I sat along the right, and the other head councilors\x{2014}Beckendorf, Silena Beauregard, and the Stoll brothers\x{2014}sat on the left. The Ares kids were supposed to send a representative, too, but all of them had gotten broken limbs (accidentally) during capture the flag, courtesy of the Hunters. They were resting up in the infirmary. Zoe started the meeting off on a positive note. \x{201c}This is pointless.\x{201d} \x{201c}Cheez Whiz!\x{201d} Grover gasped. He began scooping up crackers and Ping-Pong balls and spraying them with topping. \x{201c}There is no time for talk,\x{201d} Zoe continued. \x{201c}Our goddess needs us. The Hunters must leave immediately.\x{201d} \x{201c}And go where?\x{201d} Chiron asked. \x{201c}West!\x{201d} Bianca said. I was amazed at how different she looked after just a few days with the Hunters. Her dark hair was braided like Zoe's now, so you could actually see her face. She had a splash of freckles across her nose, and her dark eyes vaguely reminded me of someone famous, but I couldn't think who. She looked like she'd been working out, and her skin glowed faintly, like the other Hunters, as if she'd been taking showers in liquid moonlight. \"You heard the prophecy. Five shall go west to the goddess in chains. We can get fivehunters and go.\x{201c} \x{201d}Yes,\x{201c} Zoe agreed. \x{201d}Artemis is being held hostage! We must find her and free her.\x{201c} \x{201d}You're missing something, as usual,\x{201c} Thalia said. \x{201d}Campers and Hunters combined pre- vail. We're supposed to do this together.\x{201c} \x{201d}No!\x{201c} Zoe said. \x{201d}The Hunters do not need thy help.\x{201c} \x{201d}Your\x{201c} Thalia grumbled. \x{201d}Nobody has said thy in, like, three hundred years, Zoe. Get with the times.\x{201c} Zoe hesitated, like she was trying to form the word correctly. \x{201d} Yerrr. We do not need yerrr help.\x{201c} Thalia rolled her eyes. \x{201d}Forget it.\x{201c} \x{201d}I fear the prophecy says you do need our help,\x{201c} Chiron said. \x{201d}Campers and Hunters must cooperate.\x{201c} \x{201d}Or do they?\x{201c} Mr. D mused, swirling his Diet Coke under his nose like it had a fine bou- quet. \x{201d}One shall be lost. One shall perish. That sounds rather nasty, doesn't it? What if you fail because you try to cooperate?\x{201c} \x{201d}Mr. D,\x{201c} Chiron sighed, \x{201d}with all due respect, whose side are you on?\x{201c} Dionysus raised his eyebrows. \x{201d}Sorry, my dear centaur. Just trying to be helpful.\x{201c} \x{201d}We're supposed to work together,\x{201c} Thalia said stubbornly. \x{201d}I don't like it either, Zoe, but you know prophecies. You want to fight against one?\x{201c} Zoe grimaced, but I could tell Thalia had scored a point. \x{201d}We must not delay,\x{201c} Chiron warned. \x{201d}Today is Sunday. This very Friday, December twenty-first, is the winter solstice.\x{201c} \x{201d}Oh, joy,\x{201c} Dionysus muttered. \x{201d}Another dull annual meeting.\x{201c} \x{201d}Artemis must be present at the solstice,\x{201c} Zoe said. \x{201d}She has been one of the most vocal on the council arguing for action against Kronos's minions. If she is absent, the gods will de- cide nothing. We will lose another year of war preparations.\x{201c} \x{201d}Are you suggesting that the gods have trouble acting together, young lady?\x{201c} Dionysus asked. \x{201d}Yes, Lord Dionysus.\x{201c} Mr. D nodded. \x{201d}Just checking. You're right, of course. Carry on.\x{201c} \x{201d}I must agree with Zoe,\x{201c} said Chiron. \x{201d}Artemis's presence at the winter council is critical. We have only a week to find her. And possibly even more important: to locate the monster she was hunting. Now, we must decide who goes on this quest.\x{201c} \x{201d}Three and two,\" I said. Everybody looked at me. Thalia even forgot to ignore me.\x{201c}We're supposed to have five,\x{201d} I said, feeling self-conscious. \x{201c}Three Hunters, two from Camp Half-Blood. That's more than fair.\x{201d} Thalia and Zoe exchanged looks. \x{201c}Well,\x{201d} Thalia said. \x{201c}It does make sense.\x{201d} Zoe grunted. \x{201c}I would prefer to take all the Hunters. We will need strength of numbers.\x{201d} \x{201c}You'll be retracing the goddess's path,\x{201d} Chiron reminded her. \x{201c}Moving quickly. No doubt Artemis tracked the scent of this rare monster, whatever it is, as she moved west. You will have to do the same. The prophecy was clear: The bane of Olympus shows the trail. What would your mistress say? 'Too many Hunters spoil the scent.' A small group is best.\x{201d} Zoe picked up a Ping-Pong paddle and studied it like she was deciding who she wanted to whack first. \x{201c}This monster\x{2014}the bane of Olympus. I have hunted at Lady Artemis's side for many years, yet I have no idea what this beast might be.\x{201d} Everybody looked at Dionysus, I guess because he was the only god present and gods are supposed to know things. He was flipping through a wine magazine, but when everyone got silent he glanced up, \x{201c}Well, don't look at me. I'm a young god, remember? I don't keep track of all those ancient monsters and dusty titans. They make for terrible party conversa- tion.\x{201d} \x{201c}Chiron,\x{201d} I said, \x{201c}you don't have any ideas about the monster?\x{201d} Chiron pursed his lips. \x{201c}I have several ideas, none of them good. And none of them quite make sense. Typhon, for instance, could fit this description. He was truly a bane of Olympus. Or the sea monster Keto. But if either of these were stirring, we would know it. They are ocean monsters the size of skyscrapers. Your father, Poseidon