d tried to ignore the big crater that was opening in my chest. \x{201c}Grover,\x{201d} Chiron said, \x{201c}perhaps you'd let me have a word with Percy?\x{201d} \x{201c}Sure,\x{201d} he sniffled. Chiron waited, \x{201c}Oh,\x{201d} Grover said. \x{201c}You mean alone. Sure, Chiron.\x{201d} He looked at me miserably. \x{201c}See? Nobody needs a goat.\x{201d} He trotted out the door, blowing his nose on his sleeve. Chiron sighed and knelt on his horse legs. \x{201c}Percy, I don't pretend to understand proph- ecies.\x{201d} \x{201c}Yeah,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}Well, maybe that's because they don't make any sense.\x{201d} Chiron gazed at the saltwater spring gurgling in the corner of the room. \x{201c}Thalia would not have been my first choice to go on this quest. She's too impetuous. She acts without thinking. She is too sure of herself\x{201d} \x{201c}Would you have chosen me?\x{201d}\x{201c}Frankly, no,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}You and Thalia are much alike.\x{201d} \x{201c}Thanks a lot.\x{201d} He smiled. \x{201c}The difference is that you are less sure of yourself than Thalia. That could be good or bad. But one thing I can say: both of you together would be a dangerous thing.\x{201d} \x{201c}We could handle it.\x{201d} \x{201c}The way you handled it at the creek tonight?\x{201d} I didn't answer. He'd nailed me. \x{201c}Perhaps it is for the best,\x{201d} Chiron mused. \x{201c}You can go home to your mother for the holi- days. If we need you, we can call.\x{201d} \x{201c}Yeah,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}Maybe.\x{201d} I pulled Riptide out of my pocket and set it on my nightstand. It didn't seem that I'd be us- ing it for anything but writing Christmas cards. When he saw the pen, Chiron grimaced. \x{201c}It's no wonder Zoe doesn't want you along, I suppose. Not while you're carrying that particular weapon.\x{201d} I didn't understand what he meant. Then I remembered something he'd told me a long time ago, when he first gave me the magic sword: It has a long and tragic history, which we need not go into. I wanted to ask him about that, but then he pulled a golden drachma from his saddlebag and tossed it to me. \x{201c}Call your mother, Percy. Let her know you're coming home in the morn- ing. And, ah, for what it's worth\x{2026} I almost volunteered for this quest myself. I would have gone, if not for the last line.\x{201d} \x{201c}One shall perish by a parent's hand. Yeah.\x{201d} I didn't need to ask. I knew Chiron's dad was Kronos, the evil Titan Lord himself. The line would make perfect sense if Chiron went on the quest. Kronos didn't care for anyone, includ- ing his own children. \x{201c}Chiron,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}You know what this Titan's curse is, don't you?\x{201d} His face darkened. He made a claw over his heart and pushed outward\x{2014}an ancient ges- ture for warding off evil. \x{201c}Let us hope the prophecy does not mean what I think. Now, good night, Percy. And your time will come. I'm convinced of that. There's no need to rush.\x{201d} He said your time the way people did when they meant your death. I didn't know if Chiron meant it that way, but the look in his eyes made me scared to ask. I stood at the saltwater spring, rubbing Chiron's coin in my hand and trying to figure out what to say to my mom. I really wasn't in the mood to have one more adult tell me that doing nothing was the greatest thing I could do, but I figured my mom deserved an update.Finally, I took a deep breath and threw in the coin. \x{201c}O goddess, accept my offering.\x{201d} The mist shimmered. The light from the bathroom was just enough to make a faint rain- bow. \x{201c}Show me Sally Jackson,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}Upper East Side, Manhattan.\x{201d} And there in the mist was a scene I did not expect. My mom was sitting at our kitchen ta- ble with some\x{2026} guy. They were laughing hysterically. There was a big stack of textbooks between them. The man was, I don't know, thirty-something, with longish salt-and-pepper hair and a brown