alf covered with sand. On the other side of the road was a cluster of buildings too small to be a town: a boarded-up house, a taco shop that looked like it hadn't been open since before Zoe Nightshade was born, and a white stucco post office with a sign that said GILA CLAW, ARIZONA hanging crooked above the door. Beyond that was a range of hills\x{2026} but then I noticed they weren't regular hills. The coun- tryside was way too flat for that. The hills were enormous mounds of old cars, appliances, and other scrap metal. It was a junkyard that seemed to go on forever. \x{201c}Whoa,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}Something tells me we're not going to find a car rental here,\x{201d} Thalia said. She looked at Graver. \x{201c}I don't suppose you got another wild boar up your sleeve?\x{201d} Grover was sniffing the wind, looking nervous. He fished out his acorns and threw them in- to the sand, then played his pipes. They rearranged themselves in a pattern that made no sense to me, but Grover looked concerned. \x{201c}That's us,\x{201d} he said. \x{201c}Those five nuts right there.\x{201d} \x{201c}Which one is me?\x{201d} I asked. \x{201c}The little deformed one,\x{201d} Zoe suggested. \x{201c}Oh, shut up.\x{201d} \x{201c}That cluster right there,\x{201d} Grover said, pointing to the left, \x{201c}that's trouble.\x{201d} \x{201c}A monster?\x{201d} Thalia asked. Grover looked uneasy. \x{201c}I don't smell anything, which doesn't make sense. But the acorns don't lie. Our next challenge\x{2026}\x{201d} He pointed straight toward the junkyard. With the sunlight almost gone now, the hills of metal looked like something on an alien planet. We decided to camp for the night and try the junkyard in the morning. None of us wanted to go Dumpster-diving in the dark. Zoe and Bianca produced five sleeping bags and foam mattresses out of their backpacks. I don't know how they did it, because the packs were tiny, but must've been enchanted to hold so much stuff. I'd noticed their bows and quiv